hygiene
===================

Yes, declarative macros in Rust (those written using macro_rules!) do maintain hygiene by default.

What does macro hygiene mean?
Macro hygiene ensures that:

Variables declared inside a macro do not accidentally interfere with variables outside the macro, and vice versa.

This helps prevent name collisions and unexpected shadowing.

Yes, by default, in Rust’s declarative macros (macro_rules!), it is impossible for a macro writer’s internal variables to collide with variables from macro users' code, because of macro hygiene.

